      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the science.\n\nThe burning sensation during HIIT is primarily caused by the accumulation of lactic acid in your muscles. As I mentioned earlier, lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic metabolism, which occurs when your muscles don't have enough oxygen to generate energy.\n\nWhen your muscles rely on anaerobic metabolism, they break down glucose to produce energy, resulting in the production of lactic acid. This process is catalyzed by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase, which converts pyruvate into lactic acid.\n\nThe lactic acid buildup leads to a range of physiological responses, including:\n\n1. Increased muscle fatigue: Lactic acid can disrupt muscle function, leading to feelings of fatigue and weakness.\n2. Muscle soreness: The accumulation of lactic acid can cause muscle damage, leading to soreness and inflammation.\n3. pH imbalance: Lactic acid can also disrupt the pH balance of your muscles, leading to a decrease in muscle function.\n\nThe burning sensation you experience during HIIT is often described as a sharp, stabbing pain that can be intense. This is thought to be caused by the activation of nociceptors, specialized",
